      "content": "When a user runs `curl -OJ <url>` or `curl -LO <url>` , a malicious server can force the response to be saved as .curlrc in the working directory. If the user executes the download from their home directory (a common workflow), the attacker overwrites ~/.curlrc. Subsequent curl invocations automatically load this configuration file before processing command-line arguments, allowing the attacker to silently exfiltrate, overwrite local files or execute commands.\n",
